  <h1>Persona</h1>

  <p>
    The persona is the mask. It is the version of yourself that you show to the world.
    Not fake exactly, but selective. It is shaped by what is expected of you.
  </p>

  <p>
    When someone asks “who are you,” most people answer with roles. A name, a job, a
    background, a set of traits. All of this belongs to the persona. It is useful.
    Without it, social life would fall apart. You need a way to relate to others.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the danger is forgetting that it is a mask.
  </p>

  <p>
    Over time, many people become identical with their persona. They begin to believe
    that the role they play is who they truly are. The worker becomes only a worker.
    The “nice person” becomes trapped in being nice. The spiritual person becomes
    attached to appearing wise.
  </p>

  <p>
    This creates a split. The outer image is maintained, while the inner life is
    neglected. Thoughts, emotions, and impulses that do not fit the mask are pushed
    away. They do not disappear. They sink into the unconscious.
  </p>

  <p>
    The more rigid the persona becomes, the more pressure builds beneath it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Eventually this shows up as anxiety, emptiness, or a feeling of being false.
    A person may succeed outwardly while feeling hollow inside. This is the cost of
    living only through the mask.
  </p>

  <p>
    The goal is not to destroy the persona. It has a function. The goal is to see it
    clearly and not mistake it for the whole self.
  </p>

  <p>
    When you loosen identification with the mask, something else begins to appear.
    A more honest movement. Less controlled. Less concerned with approval.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the beginning of a real relationship with yourself.
  </p>

  <p>
    You still play roles. You still move through the world. But you are no longer
    completely inside the performance. You can step in and out of it.
  </p>

  <p>
    The persona becomes a tool instead of a prison.
  </p>

